<p>My nameâ€™s <a href="https://matthewelsom.com">Matthew</a>, and I built this <a href="http://jekyllrb.com/">Jekyll-based</a> tool that you can use to generate and document product or system user interface (UI) patterns in a simple <a href="https://jekyllstyleguide.com">Style Guide</a>.</p>

<h2 id="why">Why?</h2>

<p>There are a lot of really great style guide methods, tools and <a href="http://styleguides.io">examples</a> out thereâ€¦ but, I struggled to find one that was:</p>

<ul>
  <li>easy and quick to use,</li>
  <li>simple to maintain,</li>
  <li>a match for my current workflow,</li>
  <li>flexible enough to use on a wide variety of projects.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="requirements">Requirements</h2>

<p>I decided that the following requirements would meet my needs:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Use only <a href="https://jekyll.rb">Jekyll</a> as a pre-requisit</li>
  <li>Use HMTL/CSS/JS to build a web component, template, etc. (I called these â€˜patternsâ€™)</li>
  <li>Track the â€˜maturityâ€™ of a pattern - i.e. is it ready to use, or not?</li>
  <li>Automatically add all patterns into a â€˜Roadmapâ€™</li>
  <li>Enable simple documentation for developers, designers and product owners to use</li>
  <li>Provide a style guide container or â€˜shellâ€™ that is unobtrusive and easy to visually customize</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="help">Help</h2>

<p>To get started using this tool check out these useful pages:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Read the <a href="/docs/about/02-design-principle.html">design principles</a></li>
  <li>Setup and <a href="/docs/about/01-getting-started.html">installation</a> info</li>
  <li>Learn how to <a href="/docs/about/01-getting-started.html#adding-patterns">add patterns</a>, and <a href="/docs/about/01-getting-started.html#adding-documentation">documentation</a></li>
  <li>Understand the pattern <a href="/docs/about/03-maturity.html">maturity</a> scale</li>
  <li>View all patterns in the <a href="/docs/about/04-roadmap.html">Roadmap</a></li>
</ul>

